@EleanorWillisE I‚Äôm really sorry Eleanor but I‚Äôve always struggled a bit with frameworks. I‚Äôm reading more about humanist psychology & Buddhism than anything else at the moment, trying hard to hold true to my core & strong belief in humanity. Consequentialism‚Äôs presence is fairly constant too...

I got sidetracked listening. And chairing. But what an amazing day. So much to think about, not least our final session on Equity, exploring the impact of Covid-19 on mental health, palliative care & people living with disabilities. Somber but highly informative. #PandemicEthics

Now Silvia Camporesi, one of our @IMEweb Trustees, talks us through the ethical challenges that arise in accelerating clinical research trials in a pandemic. To what degree is it acceptable to compromise usual ethical standards? When does this become immoral...? #PandemicEthics

Finally, reflections on health & social inequalities...starkly exposed by Covid & non-Covid harms. We need to examine the extent & scope of our duties. ‚ÄòThe pandemic should reinforce our responsibilities...‚Äô

A powerful overview from @DrJohnChisholm many thanks
#PandemicEthics

Debating the ethical position on timing for second dose of Covid vaccine. ‚ÄòPolicy change is not irrational‚Äô & allowed in law. No legal recourse against doctors for change to consent mid-treatment. Relates in part to the contemporaneous nature of informed consent #PandemicEthics https://t.co/ghNrh0AVAV

Health professionals should not accept unreasonable levels of risk. We are working in highly uncertain circumstances. Risks of moral distress & moral injury are significantly elevated. Feelings of guilt, shame & subsequent burnout can be consequences... #PandemicEthics #ime2021

Decisions can only be ethically defensible if accountability for reasonableness, open & transparent with appropriate oversight & governance. We need to work with & inform the public. Drs need reassurance that they will not be prosecuted for following best evidence #PandemicEthics

We rely on law surrounding organ donation to inform resource allocation decisions. Decisions which must be reasonable, based on best clinical data & opinion and coherent ethical principles & reasoning... #PandemicEthics https://t.co/JEudNQASLG
Talking us through @TheBMA‚Äôs contribution to ethical support and @gmcuk guidance for doctors working in pandemic but what if demand outstrips capacity...? #PandemicEthics

‚ÄòA dark & difficult period for so many people all around the world...‚Äô widening inequalities, challenge to minimise harm, loneliness, moral distress, human vaccination trials, working at or beyond competence, safety, mental health burden...some of what we face #pandemicethics https://t.co/2HGUPRc4Yx
